Power outages are very common is Laos, but not often planned. After about 5-6pm usually, power usually cuts off for the rest of the night. In a more restful atmosphere, like in the Lao countryside, it’s not that big of a deal. Skip fendering your books, and read by the firelight.

3 – Get a sense of place. Live in the moment you’re in. Here in Laos, this is perhaps too easy. The seasons are distinct–the humid monsoon, and the drier winters. There are often several seasons a day, reflecting the Polish poem about a sunrise after a thunderstorm, and the cirrus clouds and reversions of temperature and weather, negotiating equidistant to either end of the spectrum. An Englishman once told me that he found the sky here too orange for his eyes. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T8f59m0KdN0

There are communities to be found everywhere. Village boys and girls play down by the river and those without bikes don’t often get to go far. In the city, try some basketball, join a stammtisch or pub conversation group, fish some cans and lures for pike behind the university, learn the Laotian language (these days it’s not that hard) in your university classroom.
